{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638838"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17742"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17742"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.1,0.17,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74802"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17742"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60288"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5572"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24414"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74802"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old gentleman from South Asia presents with a 2 month history of cough with occasional haemoptysis, weight loss and night sweats.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a chest X-ray abnormality commonly associated with pulmonary tuberculosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pericardial effusion","Mediastinal shift","Pleural effusion","Lower lobe consolidation","Upper lobe infiltrates"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpper lobe infiltrates\u003C/strong\u003E are a classic finding in pulmonary tuberculosis, particularly in reactivation cases. The upper lobes are more commonly affected due to the higher oxygen tension, which favours the growth of \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in tuberculosis, but it is not as common as upper lobe infiltrates. It is more often associated with primary tuberculosis or as a complication of reactivation disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericardial effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare complication of tuberculosis, known as tuberculous pericarditis. It is not a typical finding on a chest X-ray for pulmonary tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELower lobe consolidation\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with bacterial pneumonia rather than tuberculosis, which typically affects the upper lobes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMediastinal shift\u003C/strong\u003E is not a direct feature of tuberculosis. It may occur secondary to large pleural effusions or lung volume loss, but it is not a primary finding in tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary tuberculosis often presents with upper lobe infiltrates on chest X-ray.","Cavitation is a common radiological finding in reactivation tuberculosis.","Hilar lymphadenopathy is more common in primary tuberculosis, especially in children."],"references":["Nel M, Franckling-Smith Z, Pillay T, Andronikou S, Zar HJ. Chest Imaging for Pulmonary TB-An Update. Pathogens. 2022 Jan 26;11(2):161. doi: 10.3390/pathogens11020161. PMID: 35215104; PMCID: PMC8878790.","Koh WJ, Jeong YJ, Kwon OJ, Kim HJ, Cho EH, Lew WJ, Lee KS. Chest radiographic findings in primary pulmonary tuberculosis: observations from high school outbreaks. Korean J Radiol. 2010 Nov-Dec;11(6):612-7. doi: 10.3348/kjr.2010.11.6.612. Epub 2010 Oct 29. PMID: 21076586; PMCID: PMC2974222.","Rastoder E, Shaker SB, Naqibullah M, Wille MMW, Lund M, Wilcke JT, Seersholm N, Jensen SG. Chest x-ray findings in tuberculosis patients identified by passive and active case finding: A retrospective study. J Clin Tuberc Other Mycobact Dis. 2019 Jan 9;14:26-30. doi: 10.1016/j.jctube.2019.01.003. PMID: 31720415; PMCID: PMC6830123."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60288"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17742"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60288"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T09:35:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T19:03:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10456"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74802"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","